<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Terracotta Watering Pots Work</h2>

  <p>
    Water slowly seeps through porous clay walls into surrounding soil. As soil dries, more water is released.
  </p>

  <p>
    This creates:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>self-regulating moisture levels</li>
    <li>reduced evaporation</li>
    <li>steady hydration over time</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    It’s one of the most passive watering systems available.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why They Work Well for Vacation Watering</h2>

  <p>
    Unlike timers or drip systems, terracotta pots respond to actual soil conditions rather than fixed schedules.
  </p>

  <p>
    This means:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>less risk of overwatering</li>
    <li>better adaptation to weather changes</li>
    <li>more consistent soil moisture</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    They’re simple but reliable when set up properly.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Makes a Good Vacation Watering Pot</h2>

  <h3>Unglazed Terracotta</h3>
  <p>
    Allows water to move through the surface.
  </p>

  <h3>Sealed Design</h3>
  <p>
    Prevents water loss from the top.
  </p>

  <h3>Adequate Capacity</h3>
  <p>
    Must last the full duration you’re away.
  </p>

  <h3>Consistent Porosity</h3>
  <p>
    Ensures predictable water release.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Matching Capacity to Time Away</h2>

  <p>
    The biggest mistake is underestimating how much water plants need over time.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>container size or bed volume</li>
    <li>plant water needs</li>
    <li>weather conditions</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In many cases, multiple pots or larger capacity is required for longer trips.
  </p>
</section>

